00:00:00.780 --> 00:00:08.510
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington D.C.

00:00:08.510 --> 00:00:11.190
&gt;&gt; Patrick Anderson: Good
afternoon, I'm Patrick Anderson.

00:00:11.190 --> 00:00:13.200
I review fiction for
the Washington Post.

00:00:13.200 --> 00:00:14.970
And, I have the pleasure
this afternoon

00:00:14.970 --> 00:00:18.630
of introducing our next
speaker Justin Cronin.

00:00:18.630 --> 00:00:23.110 position:56%
I'll try to be brief, because I
suspect most of you are already fans

00:00:23.110 --> 00:00:26.300
of his "Passage" trilogy.

00:00:26.300 --> 00:00:28.440
But, here are a few basic facts.

00:00:28.440 --> 00:00:31.730
Justin was born near Boston.

00:00:31.730 --> 00:00:36.070
Attended Harvard in the
Iowa writers workshop.

00:00:36.070 --> 00:00:39.060
Then taught writing and literature

00:00:39.060 --> 00:00:41.010
at La Salle University
in Philadelphia.

00:00:41.010 --> 00:00:44.050
And, then at Rice University
at Houston where he

00:00:44.050 --> 00:00:45.540
and his family still live.

00:00:45.540 --> 00:00:53.850
In 2001 and 2004 Justin published
two fine novels "Marian O'Neal"

00:00:53.850 --> 00:00:58.620
and the "Summer Guest"
that won admiring reviews.

00:00:58.620 --> 00:00:59.960
Won some prizes.

00:00:59.960 --> 00:01:04.440
And, then quietly expired the
way that most literary novels do.

00:01:04.440 --> 00:01:07.320
But, a few years later
Justin was talking

00:01:07.320 --> 00:01:08.620
to his eight-year-old daughter.

00:01:08.620 --> 00:01:14.880
Who gave him the idea for writing
a very different sort of novel.

00:01:14.880 --> 00:01:20.870 position:56%
I hope he'll tell you the full story
because it's a wonderful story.

00:01:20.870 --> 00:01:23.480
But, I'll just say that
his daughter's idea lead

00:01:23.480 --> 00:01:26.710
to his great trilogy of
"The Passage", "The Twelve"

00:01:26.710 --> 00:01:28.210
and "The City of Mirrors".

00:01:28.210 --> 00:01:34.900
It also led to what I will
discretely call seven figure sales

00:01:34.900 --> 00:01:36.730
of both his trilogy
and movie rights.

00:01:36.730 --> 00:01:44.870
Someone said that this story has
caused countless American novelists

00:01:44.870 --> 00:01:50.200
to follow their children around
saying, sweetheart have you thought

00:01:50.200 --> 00:01:53.710
up a really good idea for me yet?

00:01:53.710 --> 00:01:57.310
But, the truth is that the
vast majority of writers,

00:01:57.310 --> 00:01:59.980
if we were given the
best idea in the world.

00:01:59.980 --> 00:02:03.680
Would not bring it off with
the incredible imagination

00:02:03.680 --> 00:02:08.250
and the literary skill that
Justin brought to his trilogy.

00:02:08.250 --> 00:02:13.310
His books may begin as science
fiction but the transcend genre

00:02:13.310 --> 00:02:16.020
and are simply great
American novels.

00:02:16.020 --> 00:02:19.510
It's a great pleasure to
introduce Justin Cronin.

00:02:19.510 --> 00:02:32.310
[ Applause ]

